4.25/5  rDev -3.4%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4.25 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.25Appearance:  Pours a light  honey  color with the haze one would expect from a Hefe Weissbier.  Shimmering gold in the glass.  Brilliant fine textured cap with good lacing.
Aroma:  Clove accented spices with ripe yellow fruit undertones.  No noticeable hop presence.
Taste:  Very gentle in a sophisticated way.  This beer displays good manners.  Not as full flavored as I've experienced in the past which could be due to it's age.  Bottling date is 20 OCT 15 and it certainly wasn't kept under refrigeration since then.  Perhaps not since it left the Brewery.  Some other subdued flavors of banana and/or something similar but not enough to identify let alone quantify.
Overall:  I cannot rate this based on what it may have been, only what it is.  I bought it for the tasting and figured it would still be ok and it's just that, ok.  In the past I've had other Bavarian Hefes that were much fresher and were quite frankly much better.  This one seemed like a slightly deflated balloon. 989 charactersSquire123, May 07, 2016
4.41/5  rDev +0.2%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.25Poured from 22 oz. bottle into a weizen glass.  It pours a cloudy, golden color with an enormous, fluffy, egg-white head and thick lacing. It's a beautiful pour. It smells of cloves, banana, lemon, and yeast. What a delicious beer! It is  just the right blend of sweet and tart. The clove taste is huge but there is also some sweet banana and citrus. I think it improves as it warms in the glass.  It has a nice, creamy mouthfeel with moderate carbonation, and it's ABV of 5.4% is barely noticeable. Overall, this is clearly one of the finest examples of Hefeweizen brewed in the world.  It is equally appropriate accompanying a good meal (preferably German) or for casual drinking. Sehr gut! 692 charactersMacMalt, May 07, 2016
