4.55/5  rDev +3.4%look: 5 | smell: 5 | taste: 4 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 5Have I really never reviewed this?
One of those benchmark beers against which others are measured, the appearance, with it's huge rocky head and cloudy, hyperactive golden body are gorgeous.
On the clove-forward end of the spectrum, just a hint of banana and no real bubblegum presence. Intoxicating.
Rich flavor that I look for in a real German hefe with lemony edges around a smooth, soft wheat body. Just a touch of sweetness to the finish with the clove suggested on the back end.
Not quite as carbonated as others but with a full, round mouthfeel that so many American imitators fall short of. This is as drinkable as the style gets and consistently hits the spot. 673 charactersmalcontent, Jun 03, 2009
4.43/5  rDev +0.7%look: 4.5 | smell: 4 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4 |  overall: 5Pours a honeyed brown with a billowy white, creamy head with yeast in evident, hazy suspension. Excellent head retention throughout.
The smell is exactly what you would expect, with yeast, clove and banana with some floral notes. Nice but not overdone. A powdery baseball card bubblegum starts to show up towards the end.
Starts with a wheaty lemony tartness, there's a pinch of bitterness and spice in the middle all leading to a clean, dry finish with mild elements of banana all throughout. The clove lingers nicely in the aftertaste as does a hint of orange peel zest. 
Has a crisp and clean mouthfeel and a medium amount of carbonation, perfect for a hot and hazy day.
If I had to sum this beer up in a word that word would be refined. If I had to use more words I would say it's pretty much a textbook hefeweisen and a benchmark for the style. Highly drinkable. But it's a notch below Franziskaner and Denison's in my eyes. 933 charactersMeisterBurger, Jun 03, 2009
